summary.seg: This paper manuscript dating from the 15th century comprises a copy of Thucydides, History of the Peloponnesian War and three prefixed pieces concerning the work and life of the Athenian historian. The text of the History ends with an anonymous epigram in elegiac verses taken from the Palatine Anthology.

The scribe of the manuscript has been identified as Demetrios Angelos, a Byzantine humanist and physician in the hospital of the Xenon of the Kral, in Constantinople. Angelos was among those scholars who chose to remain in the city following its capture by the Turks in May 1453 and thus did not take part in the important waves of migration to Italy. He is known to have purchased, gathered or copied numerous manuscripts and is thought to have been active from the second quarter of the 15th century as a pupil of Johannes Argyropulus (1416-1486) until 1476.

The approximately thirty works he copied not only cover medicine and philosophy, but also history, in which he showed a profound interest. He left annotations in other manuscripts of Thucydides such as Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, grec 1636 and is suspected by some scholars to have owned and studied Vatican City, Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana, Ottobonianus gr. 211 , which is, textually speaking, very closely related to Kk.5.19.

Another manuscript of Thucydides, Florence, Biblioteca Medicea Laurenziana, Plut. 69.16
was also copied by Demetrios Angelos. It actually sheds some light on several aspects of the Cambridge manuscript: on the first leaf of the Florentine one, Angelos left a note in which he confesses that he finds Thucydides’ work difficult to understand. That detail may explain why, in the Cambridge manuscript, he felt the need to add in the lower margin two sketches depicting descriptive passages of the text which he might have found hard to picture (ff. 57v, 77r).

The first sketch in the Cambridge manuscript, on f. 57v, representing the Phaleric Walls, which used to join the city of Athens and the harbour of Phalerum, has a counterpart on f. 57r of the Florence manuscript. The second sketch however, illustrating the fortifications of the city of Plataea, is only present in the Cambridge manuscript (f. 77r).

This manuscript also counts among the several witnesses of our copyist’s taste for one specific epigram of the Palatine Anthology about Thucydides (Anthologia Palatina ix, 583). Although he is not the only one to have made use of that epigram as a refined way to conclude the work of the Athenian historian, it seems to occupy a great importance in his copies. Indeed, he not only inscribed the poem in red-ink letters in our manuscript, but also copied it five times successively at the end of the Florence manuscript. He even added his own corrections to the epigram in the aforementioned BnF grec 1636, and, in some of his own copies of Galen’s works, he transformed the content, regardless of the metre, in order to adapt the epigram to the famous physician and the subject of medicine (see:
Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, grec 2154 and
Vatican City, Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana, Urbinas gr. 67 ).

supportDesc.foliation: [i-ix] + 1-309 + [x-xviii]. Modern foliation in pencil in Arabic numerals in the top right-hand corner, recto.

collation.p:
The manuscript now consists of 39 quaternions: quires 1-20 and 22-38 are regular quaternions, quire 21 lacks one folio without loss of text, quire 39 two folios.
Quires 1-208 ff. 1r-160v
Quire 218-1 ff. 161r-167v (one folio cancelled after 166v without loss of text)
Quires 22-388 ff. 168r-303v
Quire 398-2 ff. 304r-309v
Henry Bradshaw (1831-1886) added notes about the cancelled or lost folios on ff. 166v and 309v.

supportDesc.condition: In good condition; folios are yellowed and stained. Some leaves have been torn and repaired at the time of the binding with paper patches, in particular ff. 1 and 309. Humidity and water stains are found throughout the volume, along with brown and orange stains. It contains occasional worm holes (e.g. ff. 62-66)

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 1r-309r: A single column of 26 lines. Written space 205 130

handNote.p: B. Mondrain has identified the copyist of the manuscript as the Constantinopolitan physician, scribe and scholar Demetrios Angelos Angelos, Demetrios active in the 15th century, in a slightly slanting and much ligatured mixed minuscule practised scholar's hand.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript letter endings are often used and they do not appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are curved and joined to accents; circumflex accent is linkd to the omega. The trema is consistently traced over ypsilon; mute iota is absent.
Demetrios' handwriting is characterized by the beta with an elongated vertical line and ligatures with rho drawn up, traced in a single line and often with small closed loops.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper point, lower comma, full stop and marginal quotation marks. Deletions are done by strikethrough in red ink (f. 271v)

The handwriting in the rubricated notes, title headings and the final epigram, though presenting the same general characteristics as the one of the main text, is less neat and thicker in appearance. It occasionally seems to have been slightly affected by some blotting effect (e.g. f. 225v). It also regularly appears very faded.

decoDesc.decoNote: Major initials in red ink flourished with vegetative ornaments mark the start of a new text or a new book section of Thucydides’ Histories on ff. 1r, 5v, 8v, 10r, 53r, 88r, 125r, 170r, 202v, 272v. Some title headings of the manuscript are followed by ornamental line fillers drawn in red ink (e.g. ff. 170r, 202v).
Some minor red-ink initials are written within the body of the text along with some rubricated marginal notes.

The manuscript contains two sketches drawn in red ink in the lower margins of ff. 57v and 77r. The first sketch illustrates lines 12 to 16 of f. 57v, corresponding to Histories, Book II, 13, 7. It consists of a map representing the city of Athens on the left, the harbour of Phalerum on the right, and the Phaleric walls joining the two. The scribe also provided the drawing with some informative inscriptions using words directly borrowed from the text of Thucydides. Those include indications of distances in Greek numerals and of the guarded (φυλαττόμενον) and unguarded areas (ἀφύλακτον) on the map. Although the second sketch is found on f. 77r, it illustrates lines 2 to 8 of f. 76v, which corresponds to Histories, Book II, 15, 4. It shows the city walls of Plataea reinforced by a wooden structure made to ensure the protection of the city from the siege of the Lacedaemonians. Although the sketch was originally accompanied by three inscriptions, the one located below the sketch is now lost to trimming. The two other ones are Πλαταία (“Plataea”), which is written within the top circle representing the city of Plataea, and ξύλινον τεῖχος (“wooden wall”), located on the right side of the sketch.
Ornamental chevrons precede the remaining words which the scribe was unable to fit in the last line of a page (e.g. ff. 124r, 125r).

additions.p:
The notes mark important passages, mostly speeches, with a mention of the type of speech in abbreviated forms: δημηγορία ("public oration”), ἀπόκρισις (“response”) or ἀπολογία (“defence”). Those mentions are followed by one indication of the identity of the speaker and another one on the persons to whom the speech is addressed. Some of the red ink notes are only meant to clarify the meaning of Thucydides’ text. The rubricated notes are on ff.:

Some notes in Latin have been written by an early modern reader on ff. 17r (templum Iunonis) and 100v (pulchra omnino).

The numbers of the books of Thucydides have been added in the upper margin of rectos in Greek numerals from f. 10r, along with the Arabic numerals standing for the modern chapter divisions in a dark brown ink, e.g. f. 19v, lines 4 and 34, f. 20r, line 17. Richard Porson Porson, Richard, 1759-1808 (1759-1808), Regius Professor of Greek at Cambridge, was allowed to borrow the manuscript in April 1802 and the numbers of the books may have been added by him.

binding.p: Bound by Wiseman of Cambridge (first half of 19th century), and signed on lower margin of first marbled endleaf, verso.
Binding in pale brown full leather covering over millboards. Marbled paper endleaves.

The volume is wrapped in a very worn black leather chemise covering the whole binding, save the head and tail of the spine. The name of the author and the classmark are gold-tooled on the spine of the chemise: Kk Thucydides 5 19.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in Constantinople by the Byzantine physician and humanist scholar, Demetrios Angelos Angelos, Demetrios in all likelihood between the second quarter of the 15th century and year 1476 when he is last attested. He is believed to have died in 1479 (cf. Mondrain 2010, p. 299, 304).

provenance.p: In the late 15th or early 16th century, the manuscript was certainly brought to Italy by Byzantine émigrés.

At some point, it came into the possession of the Italian humanist and Chancellor of the Republic of Genoa (1514) Benedetto Tagliacarne Tagliacarne, Benedetto, 1480-1536 , also known as Benedictus Theocrenus, whose mark of ownership (Benedicti Theocreni) is found in the upper margin of f. 1r. It is likely to have been seized along with the rest of his goods by the soldiers of the Holy Roman Empire during the sack of Genoa in 1522.

Between 1697 and 1714 the manuscript came into the possession of
John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : number 982 in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL, MS Oo.7.50.2, compiled by Thomas Tanner (1674-1735) after the publication of Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697).
